After **11** months, this issue can still be perfectly reproduced with the steps I described above. To describe this issue in a sentence, the problem is the code does not recompile when I start in debug mode and there is an already compiled version.

Well, I can create an issue at their Github for sure, but I need to ask a followup question on that, because it would be easier for the both of us in the future if I could determine where the issue is coming from.

With that said, the reasoning for creating this issue in the flutter repo was that given these 2 commands:
```
flutter --no-color test --machine --plain-name calculate test/unit/test.dart

flutter --no-color test --machine --start-paused --plain-name calculate test/unit/test.dart
```

where the first one for the 'normal' run and the second one is for 'debug' the only difference is the `--start-paused` flag.

Running `flutter test -h`, relevant part:

```
    --start-paused                    Start in a paused mode and wait for a debugger to connect.
                                      You must specify a single test file to run, explicitly.
                                      Instructions for connecting with a debugger are printed to the console once the test has started.
```

The flag does not specify anything about compiling, it just allows an external debugger to be attached on a given url.

So to looks like to me that the `--start-paused` flag disables compilation, which seems to be an unintended (or at least undocumented) side-effect of running the command and that is why I don't think that it belongs to the Jetbrains' repo.

Edit.:

Or maybe I missed it that none of these commands is actually compiling and the compilation is done in a different step in the 'normal' run case. Haven't checked that one.

@TahaTesser I would say this describes the way I was trying to reproduce the issue on the command line and I am getting exactly the same thing as you did for the output

Okay this is very strange, but I've probably found something - and I could reproduce this multiple times:

If I edit the file `calculator.dart` and **then I click away** from IntelliJ into a different window (sometimes it's own terminal is also enough) and **then** I run the test using `Shift` + `F9`, the tests will execute in the newest version (there is no bug).

Which leaves me with this explanation:

- Flutter is an external tool technically
- IntelliJ does not autosave files after each type
- Flutter command runs properly, but it does not see the newest version of the file

On the other hand, the fact that IntelliJ has so many external tools in other frameworks leaves me wondering what the actual problem is. (For example, `npm run ...` always works properly - or did they write manual file saving for each and every other plugin action?)  Put it differently - should we file an issue at Jetbrains repository or leave this here.

I tested and verified the same behavior. I did this by doing a `watch -d -n 1 cat my_file_test.dart` 
 in an external terminal window and running tests. I simply would add some nonsense that wouldn't compile and ran the test without switching windows and it would compile successfully. The watch showed no changes. As soon as I clicked outside of IntelliJ (clicking the internal terminal didn't work for me) then the watch updated and the tests would no longer compile. Good catch, @andrasferenczi!
